are bullish about the company=E2=80=99s prospects=E2=80=9D is a useful sign=
al, =0Abut =E2=80=9Cthis press release is cheerful because they have been t=
rained to sound =0Acheerful to keep the stock up=E2=80=9D is not. If everyo=
ne knows this, all the press =0Areleases will be cheerful.=0A=0ALarge langu=
age models offer the ability to (1) more subtly dissect sentiment =0Awhen r=
eading press releases and (2) more subtlyconvey sentiment when writing =0At=
hem. Here=E2=80=99s a new paper on =E2=80=9CThe Future of Accounting: Senti=
ment Analysis in =0AAI-Rewritten SEC Filings =0A<https://papers.ssrn.com/so=
l3/papers.cfm=3Fabstract_id=3D4984337>,=E2=80=9D by Sebastian =0ALehner:=0A=
=0AThis paper examines the impact of sentiment analysis on SEC 10-K and 10-=
Q =0Afilings, focusing on the Management Discussion and Analysis (MD&A) sec=
tions. By =0Aleveraging large language models (LLMs) to rewrite the filings=
, this study =0Acompares the sentiment of original versus LLM-rewritten tex=
ts using multiple =0Asentiment analysis techniques, including dictionary-ba=
sed methods and machine =0Alearning models. The results show a notable incr=
ease in positive sentiment in =0Athe LLM-rewritten filings. Furthermore, th=
e rewritten filings were found to =0Ainfluence stock price reactions positi=
vely, indicating that AI-driven text =0Ageneration can enhance market perce=
ption.=0A=0AI don=E2=80=99t think he actually rewrote filings with LLMs, fi=
led them, and saw how =0Athe stock reacted; the point is that positive sent=
iment is correlated with =0Apositive reaction and so LLM rewritingshould le=
